Titanic Data EDA

About the Data

Titanic passenger data.

The dataset contains information about passengers aboard the RMS Titanic, which sank on April 15, 1912, after colliding with an iceberg. The data includes attributes such as travel class, age, gender, number of siblings/spouses aboard, number of parents/children aboard, ticket fare, and port of embarkation.

The dataset also contains information on whether a passenger survived the disaster.

The Titanic carried over 2,200 people, of whom more than 1,500 died, making this disaster one of the most tragic in maritime history.

Columns:

  • pclass Ticket class
  • survived Whether the passenger survived the disaster
  • name Passengers full name
  • sex Passengers gender
  • age Passengers age
  • sibsp Number of siblings/spouses aboard
  • parch Number of parents/children aboard
  • ticket Ticket number
  • fare Ticket fare
  • cabin Cabin number
  • embarked Port of embarkation (C = Cherbourg, Q = Queenstown, S = Southampton)
  • boat Lifeboat number
  • body Body identification number (if the passenger did not survive and the body was recovered)
  • home.dest Destination

The objective of this analysis is to investigate which factors may have influenced passenger survival during the RMS Titanic disaster, which occurred on April 15, 1912, after the ship collided with an iceberg.

The analysis is based on real-world data containing passenger information such as gender, age, ticket class, number of accompanying family members aboard, ticket fare, and port of embarkation.

During the analysis, various visualizations will be created to illustrate passenger distributions, demographic structure, and relationships between individual features and survival outcomes.

The goal of this analysis is not only to understand the overall profile of Titanic passengers, but above all to answer the question: who had the highest chances of survival, and which factors most significantly increased those chances.

Most missing values are found in the following columns: cabin, body, boat, home.dest, and age.

The key column from the perspective of this analysis is age, with 264 missing records.

  • Despite the missing values, I decide to keep the age column without imputation in order to:
  • avoid introducing artificial data (e.g., by filling with the median),
  • prevent distortion of the age distribution, which could affect further analyses (e.g., survival rates across different age groups).
  • As for the remaining columns with a large number of missing values (cabin, boat, body, home.dest), they are likely not essential for the basic analysis and may be excluded.

# 1. Distribution of passenger gender

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
ax = sns.countplot(
    x='sex_label',
    hue='sex_label',
    data=df,
    palette=['LightPink', '#3399FF'],
    legend=False
)

plt.title("Number of passengers by gender")
plt.xlabel("Gender")
plt.ylabel("Number of passengers")

# Adding counts and percentages on the bars
total = len(df)
for p in ax.patches:
    count = int(p.get_height())
    pct = 100 * count / total
    ax.text(
        p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2,
        p.get_height() / 2,
        f'{count}\n({pct:.1f}%)',
        ha='center',
        va='center',
        fontsize=11,
        fontweight='bold'
    )

plt.show()
The vast majority of passengers were men, who constituted the dominant group in the analyzed sample.
Women accounted for only about one third of the total number of passengers, indicating a significant gender imbalance in the distribution.

The data analysis clearly shows that although men constituted the majority of passengers on board the Titanic, women overwhelmingly dominated among those who survived the disaster.
This most likely results from the evacuation rules in place at the time in life-threatening situations, women and children were given priority when boarding the lifeboats.

# 1. Filter data: children (age  5)
children = df[df['age'] <= 5]

# 2. Group by 'survived' and count number of children
count_by_survived = children.groupby('survived').size()

# 3. Calculate percentages
percent_by_survived = (count_by_survived / count_by_survived.sum()) * 100

# 4. Create DataFrame for plotting
result_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Survived': ['No', 'Yes'],
    'Count': count_by_survived.values,
    'Percent': percent_by_survived.values
})

# 5. Bar plot
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
sns.barplot(data=result_df, x='Survived', y='Percent',hue='Survived', palette=['lightcoral', 'lightgreen'])
plt.title('Survival percentage of children (age  5)')
plt.ylabel('Percent (%)')
plt.xlabel('Survived')
plt.ylim(0, 100)

# 6. Add value labels above bars
for index, row in result_df.iterrows():
    plt.text(index, row['Percent'] + 2, f"{row['Percent']:.1f}%", 
             ha='center', fontsize=10)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Percentage of children who survived: 66.07%
Percentage of elderly passengers who survived (>65 years): 20.00%
Analysis of the relationship: Survival vs Age
1. Most passengers were between 20 and 40 years old
  • The largest number of passengers was in the 2040 age range.
  • This is also the group where the greatest variation between survival and non-survival is visible, indicating significant differences in survival chances within this range.
2. Children (010 years old) had a higher survival rate
  • In younger age groups, especially 05 years, green bars (survived) dominate over orange bars (did not survive).
  • This may reflect the evacuation priority given to children during the disaster ("women and children first").
3. Young adults (2030 years old) were the largest group of victims
  • In the 2030 age group, there are relatively many victims orange bars are high.
Possible reasons:
  • many of them traveled in lower classes (harder access to lifeboats),
  • men (especially young men) were given lower priority in the evacuation.
4. Passengers over 50 years old survived less often
  • In older age groups (over 50), the number of passengers generally decreases, but the ratio of survivors to non-survivors also worsens.
  • This suggests that older passengers may have had difficulty evacuating or were less mobile.
5. Age was an important factor in survival
  • There is a clear difference in survival rates between different age groups, indicating that age played an important role in survival chances.
  • This relationship is not linear the youngest had the highest chances, then it declines, and among the elderly survival decreases again.

# Ticket class 
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
ax = sns.countplot(
    x='pclass',
    data=df,
    hue='pclass',  
    palette='Set1',
    dodge=False,
    legend=False
)

plt.title("Number of passengers by ticket class")
plt.xlabel("Ticket class (1 = highest, 3 = lowest)")
plt.ylabel("Number of passengers")

# Calculate number of passengers in each class
counts = df['pclass'].value_counts().sort_index()
total = len(df)

# Add labels on the bars
for i, count in enumerate(counts):
    percent = count / total * 100
    ax.text(
        i, count / 2,           # text position at half the bar height
        f"{count}\n({percent:.1f}%)", 
        ha='center', va='center', color='white', fontsize=11, fontweight='bold'
    )

plt.show()
  • Most passengers traveled in 3rd class
  • 3rd class (lowest) had 709 passengers, which accounts for 54.1% of all travelers.
  • This means that over half of the passengers were in the lowest class it was the most crowded and popular section, probably due to lower prices.
  • There were significantly fewer passengers in 1st and 2nd class
  • 1st class (highest) had 323 passengers (24.7%),
  • 2nd class had 277 passengers (21.1%).
  • In total, passengers in 1st and 2nd class made up 45.9% of all travelers.

# Number of women and men in each ticket class
plt.figure(figsize=(7, 5))
ax = sns.countplot(
    data=df,
    x='pclass',
    hue='sex',           # differentiate by gender
    palette=['LightPink', '#3399FF'],
    dodge=True            # keep bars side by side
)

plt.title("Number of women and men in each ticket class")
plt.xlabel("Ticket class (1 = highest, 3 = lowest)")
plt.ylabel("Number of passengers")
plt.legend(title='Gender', labels=['Female', 'Male'])
plt.tight_layout()

# Add count and percentage inside each bar
total = len(df)

for patch in ax.patches:
    height = patch.get_height()
    x = patch.get_x() + patch.get_width() / 2

    if height == 0:
        continue  # skip bars with zero height

    percent = height / total * 100
    label = f"{int(height)}\n({percent:.1f}%)"

    # Place the label inside the bar (middle)
    ax.text(x, height / 2, label, ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10, color='black')

plt.show()
Analysis: Number of women and men in each ticket class
1. Most passengers were in 3rd class
  • Both women (216; 16.5%) and men (493; 37.6%) were most numerous in 3rd class.
  • 3rd class was by far the most crowded and also heavily male-dominated.
  • This is consistent with the earlier conclusion that 3rd class passengers made up over half of all travelers.
2. In every class, men outnumbered women
Differences in the number of men and women were visible in all classes:
  • 1st class: 179 men vs 144 women
  • 2nd class: 171 men vs 106 women
  • 3rd class: 493 men vs 216 women
This means that men were more numerous in every class group.
3. The largest gender disparity was in 3rd class
  • In 3rd class, there were more than twice as many men as women.
  • This suggests that many single men (e.g., workers, emigrants) traveled in 3rd class, which may affect further analyses regarding survival.
4. Gender distribution was more balanced in 1st class
  • In 1st class, the difference between the number of women and men was relatively the smallest.
  • This may indicate that passengers in this class traveled more often in pairs or families.

# Number of women and men in each class + number of survivors
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
ax = sns.countplot(
    data=df,
    x='pclass',
    hue='sex',
    palette=['LightPink', '#3399FF'],  # Female = pink, Male = blue
    dodge=True  # bars side by side
)

plt.title("Number of women and men in each class (with survivors)")
plt.xlabel("Ticket class (1 = highest, 3 = lowest)")
plt.ylabel("Number of passengers")
plt.legend(title='Gender', labels=['Female', 'Male'])
plt.tight_layout()

# Total number of passengers in each group (pclass, sex)
counts = df.groupby(['pclass', 'sex']).size().reset_index(name='total_count')

# Number of survivors in each group
survived_counts = df[df['survived'] == 1].groupby(['pclass', 'sex']).size().reset_index(name='survived_count')

# Merge into a single table
merged = pd.merge(counts, survived_counts, on=['pclass', 'sex'], how='left').fillna(0)

# Add labels  total inside bar, survivors above the bar
for container, sex in zip(ax.containers, df['sex'].unique()):
    for rect, pclass in zip(container, sorted(df['pclass'].unique())):
        row = merged[(merged['pclass'] == pclass) & (merged['sex'] == sex)]
        if not row.empty:
        
            total_n = int(row['total_count'].iloc[0])
            survived_n = int(row['survived_count'].iloc[0])
            
            #  Total number  inside the bar
            ax.text(
                rect.get_x() + rect.get_width()/2,
                rect.get_height()/2,
                f"{total_n}",
                ha='center', va='center', fontsize=11, color='black'
            )
            
            #  Number of survivors  near bottom of bar
            ax.text(
                rect.get_x() + rect.get_width()/2,
                2,  # small distance from bar base
                f"survived:\n{survived_n}",
                ha='center', va='bottom',
                fontsize=10, color='black'
            )

plt.show()

        color='black'
    )

plt.show()

Impact of Ticket Class on Survival Chances

1st Class (highest ticket class):

  • There are 144 women in this class, of whom 139 survived.
  • There are 179 men in this class, of whom only 61 survived.
  • This means the survival rate among women in 1st class is much higher (~97%), while among men it is about 34%.

2nd Class:

  • In 2nd class, there are 106 women, of whom 94 survived.
  • There are 171 men, of whom only 25 survived.
  • Survival rates in this class are also significantly higher for women (89%) than for men (15%).

3rd Class (lowest ticket class):

  • In 3rd class, there are 216 women, of whom 106 survived.
  • Among men, there are 493, of whom only 75 survived.

        color='black'
    )

Analysis: Survival Rate by Port of Embarkation (Embarked)

The first chart shows how many passengers from each port (Southampton, Cherbourg, Queenstown) survived the disaster.
  • The largest number of passengers boarded in Southampton, but they also had the lowest survival rate (approx. 33%).
  • Passengers from Cherbourg had the highest survival rate (approx. 55%), despite being a much smaller group.
  • Passengers from Queenstown had a survival rate similar to Southampton (approx. 36%).
Analysis: Ticket Class and Gender by Port of Embarkation

The second chart shows the passenger structure at each port broken down by ticket class (pclass) and gender (sex).

  • In Southampton, third-class men dominated, which is the group with the lowest survival rate.
  • In Cherbourg, many first-class passengers boarded, including women, which explains the higher survival rate.
  • Queenstown was a port from which many third-class passengers departed, often men from lower social classes resulting in a lower survival rate.
Final Conclusions
  • At first glance, it may appear that the port of embarkation influenced survival, but the analysis shows that the key determining factors were ticket class and passenger gender.
  • Passengers from Cherbourg were more likely to belong to first class and to be women, which significantly increased their chances of survival.
  • Passengers from Southampton and Queenstown were predominantly men from lower classes, which explains their lower survival rates.
Overall Conclusion:

The port of embarkation did not have a direct impact on survival it was only an indirect indicator of passengers social status and ticket class. These two factors (along with gender) played the most critical role in determining survival.

# Correlation of Variables with Survival

# 1. Create a new column  total number of relatives
df['relatives'] = df['sibsp'] + df['parch']

# 2. Select variables for correlation
df_corr = df[['survived', 'pclass', 'sex', 'age', 'relatives', 'embarked']].copy()

# Encode sex
df_corr['sex'] = df_corr['sex'].map({'male': 1, 'female': 0})

# Encode embarked (handles full names)
df_corr['embarked'] = df_corr['embarked'].map({
    'Southampton': 0,
    'Cherbourg': 1,
    'Queenstown': 2
})

# 3. Remove rows with missing values
df_corr = df_corr.dropna()

# 4. Compute correlation matrix
corr_matrix = df_corr.corr()

# 5. Extract correlations with 'survived'
corr_with_survived = corr_matrix[['survived']].drop('survived')

# 6. Plot heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
sns.heatmap(
    corr_with_survived,
    annot=True,
    cmap='coolwarm',
    fmt=".2f",
    cbar=True
)

plt.title("Correlation of Variables with Survival")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
The chart shows the correlation of various variables with survival ("survived"). The conclusions are as follows:
Gender (sex):
  • The correlation is -0.54, which indicates a strong negative correlation with survival. Women had significantly higher chances of survival than men.
Ticket class (pclass):
  • The correlation is -0.32, indicating a moderate negative correlation with survival. Passengers in 1st class had higher chances of survival, while those in 3rd class had lower chances.
Age (age):
  • The correlation is -0.06, suggesting a very weak correlation. Age does not have a strong impact on survival, although younger passengers may have had slightly higher chances of survival.
Number of relatives (relatives):
  • The correlation is 0.06, indicating a very weak, almost negligible correlation. The number of relatives a passenger had did not significantly affect their survival chances.
Port of embarkation (embarked):
  • The correlation is 0.11, indicating a very weak positive correlation. Passengers who embarked at certain ports may have had slightly higher chances of survival, but the effect of this variable is marginal.
Summary:
  • The strongest factor influencing survival was gender, with women having much higher survival rates.
  • Ticket class also had a noticeable impactpassengers traveling in 1st class were more likely to survive.
  • Age, number of relatives, and port of embarkation had minimal impact on survival.

4. Final Conclusions

The analysis of Titanic passenger data reveals clear relationships between gender, ticket class, age, and port of embarkation and the chances of survival.

The most important factors influencing survival:
  • Gender one of the strongest factors.
  • Women had significantly higher chances of survival than men, which confirms the evacuation rule: women and children first.
  • Ticket class (social status) first-class passengers had substantially higher chances of survival than those traveling in second and third class.
  • Age children, especially those from higher classes, had slightly higher survival chances than adult men.
  • Among elderly passengers, survival rates were lower, particularly in the lower classes.
Port of embarkation did not directly affect survival on its own, but was related to passenger profiles:
  • Passengers boarding in Cherbourg were mostly wealthier first-class travelers (high survival rate).
  • Passengers boarding in Southampton and Queenstown were mainly third-class men (low survival rate).
The most affected group:
  • Third-class men, especially those who boarded in Southampton or Queenstown.

They were accommodated in the lowest parts of the ship, had limited access to lifeboats, and evacuation priority was given to higher-class passengers. This group experienced the highest proportion of fatalities during the disaster.

Survival in the Titanic disaster depended heavily on a passengers gender and social class.
It was not random, but rather a reflection of the social inequalities and rules in force at the time.

The analysis shows that privileged groups (wealthier passengers and women) had the greatest chances of survival, while men from lower classes constituted the majority of the victims.
